      • find

        public GraphQueryBuilderStarter find()
        Description copied from interface: ChronoGraph
        Starting point for queries in this ChronoGraph instance.

        NOTE: This method requires an open transaction!

        The returned object is a query builder that is supposed to be used e.g. like this: 

         ChronoGraph g = ...;
 Set<Vertex> vertices = g.find().vertices().where("name").containsIgnoreCase("foo").toSet();
        You can also switch to a gremlin query from the builder: 
         ChronoGraph g = ...;
 g.find().vertices().where("name").containsIgnoreCase("foo").toTraversal().outE()...
        Specified by:
        find in interface ChronoGraph
        Returns:
        The new query builder instance, intended for method chaining. Never null.

      • getVertexHistory

        public java.util.Iterator<java.lang.Long> getVertexHistory(java.lang.Object vertexId)
        Description copied from interface: ChronoGraph
        Returns the history of the vertex with the given id, in the form of timestamps.

        Each returned timestamp reflects a point in time when a commit occurred that changed the vertex in question. The same commit may have simultaneously also changed other elements in the graph. Opening a transaction on this timestamp, and retrieving the vertex by id from it will produce the vertex in the state at that point in time.

        NOTE: This method requires an open transaction! The returned history will always be the history up to and including (but not after) the transaction timestamp!

        Specified by:
        getVertexHistory in interface ChronoGraph
        Parameters:
        vertexId - The id of the vertex to fetch the history timestamps for. Must not be null.
        Returns:
        An iterator over the history timestamps. May be empty, but never null. The exact ordering of the returned keys is up to the implementation. Implementations should try to return the timestamps in descending order (highest first).

      • getCommitTimestampsBetween

                                                                     long from,

        Description copied from interface: ChronoGraph
        Returns an iterator over all timestamps where commits have occurred, bounded between from and to.

      • getCommitMetadataBetween

        public java.util.Iterator<java.util.Map.Entry<java.lang.Long,java.lang.Object>> getCommitMetadataBetween(java.lang.String branch,
                                                                                                         long from,
                                                                                                         long to,
                                                                                                         org.chronos.chronodb.api.Order order)
        Description copied from interface: ChronoGraph
        Returns an iterator over the entries of commit timestamp and associated metadata, bounded between from and to.

        If the from value is greater than the to value, this method always returns an empty iterator.

        Please keep in mind that some commits may not have any metadata attached. In this case, the value component of the Map.Entry will be set to null.

        Specified by:
        getCommitMetadataBetween in interface ChronoGraph
        Parameters:
        branch - The name of the branch to consider. Must not be null, must refer to an existing branch.
        from - The lower bound of the time range to look for commits in (inclusive). Must not be negative. Must be less than or equal to the timestamp of this transaction.
        to - The upper bound of the time range to look for commits in (inclusive). Must not be negative. Must be less than or equal to the timestamp of this transaction.
        order - The order of the returned commits. Must not be null.
        Returns:
        An iterator over the commits in the given time range. The contained entries have the timestamp as the key component and the associated metadata as their value component (which may be null). May be empty, but never null.

      • getCommitTimestampsPaged

        public java.util.Iterator<java.lang.Long> getCommitTimestampsPaged(java.lang.String branch,
                                                                   long minTimestamp,
                                                                   long maxTimestamp,
                                                                   int pageSize,
                                                                   int pageIndex,
                                                                   org.chronos.chronodb.api.Order order)
        Description copied from interface: ChronoGraph
        Returns an iterator over commit timestamps in a paged fashion.

        For example, calling getCommitTimestampsPaged(10000, 100, 0, Order.DESCENDING) will give the latest 100 commit timestamps that have occurred before timestamp 10000. Calling getCommitTimestampsPaged(123456, 200, 2, Order.DESCENDING will return 200 commit timestamps, skipping the 400 latest commit timestamps, which are smaller than 123456.

        Specified by:
        getCommitTimestampsPaged in interface ChronoGraph
        Parameters:
        branch - The name of the branch to consider. Must not be null, must refer to an existing branch.
        minTimestamp - The minimum timestamp to consider (inclusive). All lower timestamps will be excluded from the pagination. Must be less than or equal to the timestamp of this transaction.
        maxTimestamp - The highest timestamp to consider (inclusive). All higher timestamps will be excluded from the pagination. Must be less than or equal to the timestamp of this transaction.
        pageSize - The size of the page, i.e. the maximum number of elements allowed to be contained in the resulting iterator. Must be greater than zero.
        pageIndex - The index of the page to retrieve. Must not be negative.
        order - The desired ordering for the commit timestamps
        Returns:
        An iterator that contains the commit timestamps for the requested page. Never null, may be empty. If the requested page does not exist, this iterator will always be empty.

      • getCommitMetadataPaged

        public java.util.Iterator<java.util.Map.Entry<java.lang.Long,java.lang.Object>> getCommitMetadataPaged(java.lang.String branch,
                                                                                                       long minTimestamp,
                                                                                                       long maxTimestamp,
                                                                                                       int pageSize,
                                                                                                       int pageIndex,
                                                                                                       org.chronos.chronodb.api.Order order)
        Description copied from interface: ChronoGraph
        Returns an iterator over commit timestamps and associated metadata in a paged fashion.

        For example, calling getCommitTimestampsPaged(10000, 100, 0, Order.DESCENDING) will give the latest 100 commit timestamps that have occurred before timestamp 10000. Calling getCommitTimestampsPaged(123456, 200, 2, Order.DESCENDING will return 200 commit timestamps, skipping the 400 latest commit timestamps, which are smaller than 123456.

        The Entries returned by the iterator always have the commit timestamp as their first component and the metadata associated with this commit as their second component. The second component can be null if the commit was executed without providing metadata.

        Specified by:
        getCommitMetadataPaged in interface ChronoGraph
        Parameters:
        branch - The name of the branch to consider. Must not be null, must refer to an existing branch.
        minTimestamp - The minimum timestamp to consider (inclusive). All lower timestamps will be excluded from the pagination. Must be less than or equal to the timestamp of this transaction.
        maxTimestamp - The highest timestamp to consider. All higher timestamps will be excluded from the pagination. Must be less than or equal to the timestamp of this transaction.
        pageSize - The size of the page, i.e. the maximum number of elements allowed to be contained in the resulting iterator. Must be greater than zero.
        pageIndex - The index of the page to retrieve. Must not be negative.
        order - The desired ordering for the commit timestamps
        Returns:
        An iterator that contains the commits for the requested page. Never null, may be empty. If the requested page does not exist, this iterator will always be empty.

      • getCommitMetadataAround

        public java.util.List<java.util.Map.Entry<java.lang.Long,java.lang.Object>> getCommitMetadataAround(java.lang.String branch,
                                                                                                    long timestamp,
                                                                                                    int count)
        Description copied from interface: ChronoGraph
        Returns pairs of commit timestamp and commit metadata which are "around" the given timestamp on the time axis.

        By default, this method will attempt to return the closest count/2 commits before and after the given timestamp. However, if there are not enough elements on either side, the other side will have more entries in the result list (e.g. if the request count is 10 and there are only two commits before the request timestamp, the list of commits after the request timestamp will have 8 entries instead of 5 to create a list of total length 10). In other words, the result list will always have as many entries as the request count, except when there are not as many commits on the store yet.

        Specified by:
        getCommitMetadataAround in interface ChronoGraph
        Parameters:
        branch - The name of the branch to execute the search on. Must refer to an existing branch, and must in particular not be null.
        timestamp - The request timestamp around which the commits should be centered. Must not be negative.
        count - How many commits to retrieve around the request timestamp. By default, the closest count/2 commits will be taken on both sides of the request timestamp. Must not be negative.
        Returns:
        A list of pairs. The keys are commit timsetamps, the corresponding values are the commit metadata objects (which may be null). The list itself will never be null, but may be empty (if there are no commits to report). The list is sorted in descending order by timestamps.

      • writeDump

        public void writeDump(java.io.File dumpFile,
                      org.chronos.chronodb.api.DumpOption... dumpOptions)
        Description copied from interface: ChronoGraph
        Creates a database dump of the entire current database state.

        Please note that the database is not available for write operations while the dump process is running. Read operations will work concurrently as usual.

        WARNING: The file created by this process may be very large (several gigabytes), depending on the size of the database. It is the responsibility of the user of this API to ensure that enough disk space is available; this method does not perform any checks regarding disk space availability!

        WARNING: The given file will be overwritten without further notice!

        Specified by:
        writeDump in interface ChronoGraph
        Parameters:
        dumpFile - The file to store the dump into. Must not be null. Must point to a file (not a directory). The standard file extension *.chronodump is recommmended, but not required. If the file does not exist, the file (and any missing parent directory) will be created.
        dumpOptions - The options to use for this dump (optional). Please refer to the documentation of the invididual constants for details.

      • readDump

        public void readDump(java.io.File dumpFile,
                     org.chronos.chronodb.api.DumpOption... dumpOptions)
        Description copied from interface: ChronoGraph
        Reads the contents of the given dump file into this database.

        This is a management operation; it completely locks the database. No concurrent writes or reads will be permitted while this operation is being executed.

        WARNING: The current contents of the database will be merged with the contents of the dump! In case of conflicts, the data stored in the dump file will take precedence. It is strongly recommended to perform this operation only on an empty database!

        WARNING: As this is a management operation, there is no rollback or undo option!

        Specified by:
        readDump in interface ChronoGraph
        Parameters:
        dumpFile - The dump file to read the data from. Must not be null, must exist, and must point to a file (not a directory).
        dumpOptions - The options to use while reading (optional). May be empty.
